status_message:
Next time you forget your password when logging into a website, blame it on Bill Gates.

Eight years ago, Gates declared that the password would soon be gone, replaced by secure tokens or Smart Cards. That never happened. Gates' prediction happened before the rapid growth of web giants such as Amazon and Facebook, which allowed millions of users to sign-up, for free, using nothing more than a password.

Convential thinking says that the password should be complicated to thwart brute force attacks, where hackers slam combination after combination into the password field. But most web sites can  easily stop these by using a captcha or timing out after a handful of failed logins. So while we're wasting our time coming up with impossible-to-remember passwords, keyloggers and phishers are having a field day breaking into our Gmail and Facebook accounts.

Gates was wrong. The password isn't dead; it's flourishing. But we need internet security to catch up.

status_message:
DARPA desperately wants to streamline health testing for the US military. To date, they've hurled millions of dollars at groups looking at new technologies which would remove the middleman -- the medic -- from the process of collecting bodily fluids. If they are successful, health care professionals may find it easier to keep tabs on solider health, remotely monitoring their patients in a fast and consistent manner. 

The agency is focusing on finding disease biomarkers in bodily specimens, such as spit, urine, or semen, which can be easily collected, even in the field. If the technology proves effective, it may provide the necessary early warning system to keep soldiers (and, possibly, civilians) healthy.

Quake-ravaged Haiti faces a long-term emergency, one that will not end in a few weeks when the media frenzy dies down.

That's why Wired has created Haiti Rewired. We believe that
better answers to the difficult questions could be created through the
collaboration of technologists, researchers, geographers,
infrastructure specialists, aid groups and others. Our writers and
editors can aggregate information, report new stories and add to the
discussion, but the focus of this effort is squarely on the thoughts,
plans and actions of our contributors.

We welcome your contributions.  Please check it out.
link_name: Haiti Rewired

status_message:
At long last, Game|Life The Video has returned. This week, we take a look at the game you're all dying to get your hands on: Super Smash Bros. Brawl.  Get a look at the new features that have impressed us the most from our hands-on time, from Final Smashes to the stage creator to the controller configuration options (which truly is an awesome idea).

And then, stick around for a very special public service announcement.

As you can see, we're still trying new things with the videos, so keep giving us your thoughts.

Producer: Annaliza Savage, Editor/Camera: Michael Lennon
link_name: Game|Life: The Video Program, Episode 2

status_message:
It's true: Game|Life has finally broken free of the shackles of the written word and our faces will now be beamed directly into your living room with the premiere of our video blog.

Watch as your lovable host Chris Kohler reviews No More Heroes and Rez HD, bringing you all the opinions you could ever possibly handle without all the strain of having to read.
(If you'd prefer text-based reviews of both games, we have those too: http://www.wired.com/gaming/gamingreviews/news/2008/02/gamereviews_0211)

We'll be back every Monday with a new episode, highlighting the things we feel so strongly about that mere prose is not enough. In the meantime, our team would love your feedback.

Producer: Annaliza Savage, Editor: Michael Lennon, Camera: John Ross
link_name: Game|Life: The Video Program, Episode One
